# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To use minimum rounds we need to complete as many tasks possible in group of 3 and remainder could be done in pair of two.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Since we will completing as many tasks possible in group of 3. Following are the cases for varied frequency of tasks: -

**Case 1: Multiple of 3**
```
freq = 9
```
When frequency is multiple of 3, freq%3 would be zero and freq/3 would be the required answer.

**Case 2: Multiple of 2 but not 3**
```
freq = 16
```
freq%3 = 1, so in order to minimize the rounds we would take (freq/3)-1 rounds of 3 and thus leaving us with 4 rounds which could be handled in pair of 2 more rounds.

**Case 3: Multiple of neither 2 or 3**
```
freq = 11
or
freq = 7
```
if freq%3 == 1, we do same as case 2
else freq%3 == 2, we use more 1 round for the remaining pair of task.

**Case 4:**
```
freq = 1
```
return -1.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(number of distinct tasks*2)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
