# Intuition
Let's understand this problem little more deeper, consider a number 10 how can we achieve it in minimum tries?
The easiest way any one can figure out is the number of times 3 jobs can be done which is 3 * 3 = 9 and we have a remainder 1.

One key thing we may observe is that 3 can be done by subtracting one from 9 and doing it as 2 jobs of 2. which means 4 can be achieved by 2 jobs of 2.

NOTE: this will work for any number except 1, for which we should return -1.

# Approach
- Find the frequency of the number using a hashmap.
- Find whether the frequency is 1, if so return -1, else
- Find the divisibility of that number by 3 and the reminder.
- If the remainder is greater than 0 then add one to the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n + m)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumRounds(int[] tasks) {
        int res=0;
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map= new HashMap();
        for(int i: tasks){
        	int count = map.getOrDefault(i, 0);
        	map.put(i, ++count);
        }
		for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> e : map.entrySet()) {
			int i = e.getValue();
			if (i == 1)
				return -1;
			res = res + i / 3;
			if (i % 3 == 0)
				continue;
			res++;
		}
		return res; 
    }
}
```

