# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If number of tasks with a difficulty is 1, only then it is not possible to complete all the tasks else we need to compute minimum rounds to complete tasks

In each round complete 3 tasks, till remaining tasks are more than 3.

Now, when for remaining tasks there are 3 possibilities:
1. Remaining tasks = 0 
- We have our answer 
(6 tasks at beginning, in 2 rounds all tasks are completed)

---

2. Remaining tasks = 1 
- Convert an already completed round of 3 tasks to 2 tasks. 
- So now we have 2 tasks remaining which can be completed in 1 round of 2 tasks. 
- Therefore add 1 more round to answer

---

3. Remaining tasks = 2
- 2 remaining tasks can be completed in 1 round of 2 tasks. 
- Therefore add 1 more round to answer

(I have used ceil function for these cases)

# Approach 1
Sort the tasks vector to group the tasks with same difficulties together

# Complexity
- Time complexity:  $$O(nlogn)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int ceil3(int curr)
    {
        return (curr/3)+(curr%3!=0);
    }
    int minimumRounds(vector<int>& tasks) 
    {
        if(tasks.size()==1) return -1;

        sort(tasks.begin(),tasks.end());

        int n=tasks.size() , ans=0 , curr=1;

        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++)
        {
            if(i==n || tasks[i]!=tasks[i-1])
            {
                if(curr==1) return -1;
                else ans+=ceil3(curr) , curr=1;
            } 
            else
            {
                curr++;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
