solutions.content:
# Approach
We can easily get element counts using LINQs GroupBy and Select. GroupBy generates an `IEnumerable` for each group key, with `.Select()` we can extract just the counts.
We then process each of these counts.
If `1` then we cant complete.
If `count % 3 == 0` then we can complete the tasks in `count / 3` rounds
If `count % 3 == 1` then we need 2 rounds of completing two tasks + `(count - 4) / 3` rounds of completing 3. `(count - 4)` since we completed 2 rounds of 2 tasks.
If `count % 3 == 1` We need to do one round of two tasks + `(count - 2) / 3` of 3 tasks.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
`O(n)` at most we have `n` groups and we need to check them all

- Space complexity:
`O(n)` at most we store counts `n` groups

# Code
``` CSharp
public class Solution {
    public int MinimumRounds(int[] tasks) {
        var groups = tasks.GroupBy(t => t).Select(t => t.Count());
        var rounds = 0;
        foreach (var count in groups) {
            if (count == 1) return -1;
            rounds += (count % 3) switch {
                0 => count / 3,
                1 => 2 + (count - 4) / 3,
                2 => 1 + (count - 2) / 3
            };
        }
        return rounds;
    }
}
```

