# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to find the minimun number of rounds in which we can complete each task of same difficulty in either *2 tasks per round or 3 tasks per round*
now any number N greater than 1 can be written in the form:
<c>    N = 2 * x + 3 * y; </c>
formally, any number *greater than 1* can be written as a sum of multiples of 2 and 3.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
So the only time we will not be able to do a task in 2 or 3 rounds is then there is only 1 task of that difficulty.
So, we create a frequency map of the various difficulties of the task and check if any of them occurs only once, if there is a task we return -1.
Otherwise, since we have to find the minimun number of rounds, we will try and do it same difficulty tasks in sets of 3 and then 2.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumRounds(vector<int>& tasks) {
        int n = tasks.size();
        map<int, int> mpp;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            mpp[tasks[i]]++;
        }

        int numberOfRounds = 0;

        for(auto it = mpp.begin(); it != mpp.end(); it++) {
            if(it -> second == 1) {
                return -1;
            }  // frequency of a task is 1, return -1.

            int freq = it -> second;

            if(freq % 3 == 2) {
                numberOfRounds += freq / 3 + 1;
            }   // we can do max freq/3 number of rounds of 3 and then we have to make 1 set of 2.
            else if(freq % 3 == 1) {
                numberOfRounds += (freq - 4) / 3 + 2;
            }   // we will make 2 sets of 2 and then remaining of them will be in sets of 3
            else {
                numberOfRounds += freq / 3;
            }   // min number of rounds = val / 3
        }
        return numberOfRounds;
    }
};
```

