# Approach
**Keep in mind we need to Return the minimum rounds required to complete all the tasks**
1. First we create unordered_map to store tasks and number of times task repeated as key and value respectively.
2. now we will go through the number of tasks(i.e. val.second) having same difficulty level(i.e. val.first)
    1. if the number of tasks is equal to 1(i.e. val.second) then, you can never complete either 2 or 3 tasks having same difficulty level in each round. In this case you will return -1.
    2. if the number of tasks is equal to 2(i.e. val.second) then, you can complete 2 tasks having same difficulty level in each round at a time. In this case you will add count = count + 1.
    3. if the number of tasks is >= 3(i.e. val.second) then, you can complete either 2 or 3 tasks having same difficulty level in each round at a time. lets understand with examples
        1. suppose we have vector, tasks = [4, 4, 4], then output will be 1, bcz we will take 3 tasks having same difficulty level(i.e. 4) at a time.
        2. suppose we have vector, tasks = [4, 4, 4, 4], then output will be 2, bcz we will not pick [[4, 4, 4], [4]] instead of picking this we will pick [[4, 4], [4, 4]].
        3. suppose we have vector, tasks = [4, 4, 4, 4, 4], then output will be 2, bcz we will not pick [[4, 4], [4, 4], [4]], instead of picking this we will pick [[4, 4, 4], [4, 4]].
